  9  /-!
 10  # The `finish` family of tactics
 11  
 12  These tactics do straightforward things: they call the simplifier, split conjunctive assumptions,
 13  eliminate existential quantifiers on the left, and look for contradictions. They rely on ematching
 14  and congruence closure to try to finish off a goal at the end.
 15  
 16  The procedures *do* split on disjunctions and recreate the smt state for each terminal call, so
 17  they are only meant to be used on small, straightforward problems.
 18  
 19  ## Main definitions
 20  
 21  We provide the following tactics:
 22  
 23    `finish`  -- solves the goal or fails
 24    `clarify` -- makes as much progress as possible while not leaving more than one goal
 25    `safe`    -- splits freely, finishes off whatever subgoals it can, and leaves the rest
 26  
 27  All accept an optional list of simplifier rules, typically definitions that should be expanded.
 28  (The equations and identities should not refer to the local context.)
 29  
 30  ## Implementation notes
 31  
 32  The variants `ifinish`, `iclarify`, and `isafe` try to restrict to intuitionistic logic. But the
 33  `done` tactic leaks classical logic:
 34  
 35  ```
 36  example {P : Prop} : ¬¬P → P :=
 37  by using_smt (do smt_tactic.intros, smt_tactic.close)
 38  ```
st     ┴
 39  
 40  They also do not work well with the current heuristic instantiation method used by `ematch`.
 41  So they are left here mainly for reference.
 42  -/
 43

111  /-
112    Normalize hypotheses. Bring conjunctions to the outside (for splitting),
113    bring universal quantifiers to the outside (for ematching). The classical normalizer
114    eliminates a → b in favor of ¬ a ∨ b.
115  
116    For efficiency, we push negations inwards from the top down. (For example, consider
117    simplifying ¬ ¬ (p ∨ q).)
118  -/

406  /-
407    The main tactics.
408  -/
409  
410  /--
411    `safe_core s ps cfg opt` negates the goal, normalizes hypotheses
412    (by splitting conjunctions, eliminating existentials, pushing negations inwards,
413    and calling `simp` with the supplied lemmas `s`), and then tries `contradiction`.
414  
415    If this fails, it will create an SMT state and repeatedly use `ematch`
416    (using `ematch` lemmas in the environment, universally quantified assumptions,
417    and the supplied lemmas `ps`) and congruence closure.
418  
419    `safe_core` is complete for propositional logic. Depending on the form of `opt`
420    it will:
421  
422    - (if `opt` is `case_option.force`) fail if it does not close the goal,
423    - (if `opt` is `case_option.at_most_one`) fail if it produces more than one goal, and
424    - (if `opt` is `case_option.accept`) ignore the number of goals it produces.
425  -/

503  /--
504    `clarify [h1,...,hn] using [e1,...,en]` negates the goal, normalizes hypotheses
505    (by splitting conjunctions, eliminating existentials, pushing negations inwards,
506    and calling `simp` with the supplied lemmas `h1,...,hn`), and then tries `contradiction`.
507  
508    If this fails, it will create an SMT state and repeatedly use `ematch`
509    (using `ematch` lemmas in the environment, universally quantified assumptions,
510    and the supplied lemmas `e1,...,en`) and congruence closure.
511  
512    `clarify` is complete for propositional logic.
513  
514    Either of the supplied simp lemmas or the supplied ematch lemmas are optional.
515  
516    `clarify` will fail if it produces more than one goal.
517  -/
